<TITLE> Blast kills three militants in NW Pakistan:police </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 ISLAMABAD, Jan 30 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Three suspected militants were killed on Wednesday when explosives they were handling went off accidentally near Pakistan's northwestern city of Peshawar, police said. The pre-dawn blast occurred on the outskirts of the capital of North West Frontier Province where a recent wave of violence, blamed on al Qaeda-linked militants based in the tribal belt along the Afghan border, has killed hundreds of people. "They were probably handling explosives at a house when it detonated prematurely, leading to the death of three men on the spot," Tahir Khan, a senior police official, told Reuters. "Police have recovered explosives and arrested the owner of the rented house." Violence has escalated in northwestern Pakistan in recent weeks with militants targeting security forces with suicide bombs and attacking military bases. Most of the violence has been concentrated in the Waziristan region. At least 10 people, most of them believed to be of Arab origin according to intelligence officials, were killed in North Waziristan late on Monday by a missile residents said was fired from a US drone aircraft at a house near Mir Ali, the region's main town. US forces in Afghanistan have launched similar attacks on al Qaeda targets on the Pakistani side of the border several times in recent years. Neither US nor Pakistani authorities confirm US missile strikes inside Pakistani territory. Pakistan says it will not tolerate violations of its territorial sovereignty and reports of such attacks are embarrassing for the allia
